Aristotle enumeratas four different kinds of reasoning, to which the colloquial form (τὸ διαλέγεσθαι) was applied, λόγοι transnatat, διαλεκτικοί, πειραστικοί, and lgrortaol a. The first are demonstrative reasonings, from the proper and axiomatic principles of a given subject. The second, or dialectic reasonings in the Aristotelian sense of the term, arc those derived from general principles of probability, such as the opinions of the majority of mankind, or of philosophers. The third are only a special application of probable reasonings to exposa the ignorance of pre- tenders in science¹. The fourth are fallacious reasonings, from apparent but not real probabilities. In a sub· sequent passage, he distinguishes between ἐριστικοί and coccorano& the former being such as employ fallacy merely for a display of skill; the latter, for pecuniary profit. Hence he defines σοφιστική as χρηματιστικῆ τις ἀπὸ σοφίας φαινομένην. These distinctions however will be of comparatively late origin3 after the various applicatione of the original methodos Zeno had rendered specific names necessary.

Tho eristic or sophistic was, as might naturally be expected, the earliest of these special developments of the dialectis method. The arguments of Zeno himself had no small affinity to sophistry3 and the state of philosophy at that period was such as naturally to promote further advance in the same directicn.
